Obesity and Education Background

We are interested in examining a relationship between obesity and educational level.

The education data set in the file education.csv summarizes education level in Wisconsin by zip code and sex with the percentage of men and women age 25 and older who have a bachelor’s degree or higher. There is one row per zip code and separate columns for females and males with a small amount of missing data.

The obesity data is broken down more finely: we have one row for each zip code, sex, and age range.

In order to join these data sets, we will want to reshape each so that there is one row per zip code and sex. The reshaped education data set will have columns zip, sex, and pct_bachelors with the percentage of individuals aged 25 and older of the given sex in that zip code with at least a bachelors degree. The reshaped obesity data set will have columns zip, sex and pct_obese with the estimated population percentage of adult individuals in the given sex and zip code that are obese (BMI > 30). We will only estimate these percentages in zip codes with no missing data among adults.

Note that our adult educational variable and adult obesity variables are calculated on different subsets of the adult populations within each zip code and sex (25+ for education, 18+ for obesity). This is okay as our comparisons are at the zip code level and not the individual person level.

The first few problems involve exploring and reshaping the individual data sets. Later problems ask you to do some data analysis with these reshaped and/or joined data sets.

This data transformation will require reshaping data, changing data values, and transforming column names. There are (at least) two ways to think about doing this:

Solution

  • It is easier to use rename() to change the column names to the desired values.
  • Both solutions are below.
## This code creates a data file temp which contains the common code for the two solutions
temp = education_orig %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip))
## rename and then reshape
education = temp %>% 
  rename(female = pct_f_bach,
         male = pct_m_bach) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = contains("male"),
               names_to = "sex",
               values_to = "pct_bachelors") %>% 
  arrange(zip, sex)

education %>% 
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

  mutate(sex = recode(sex,
                      "pct_m_bach" = "male",
                      "pct_f_bach" = "female"))

Solution

obesity = read_csv("../../data/obesity.csv") %>% 
  mutate(obese_pop = pop * (obese / n),
         non_obese_pop = pop - obese_pop) %>% 
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip))

adult_pop_sum = obesity %>% 
  filter(age != "05-17") %>% 
  group_by(zip, sex) %>% 
  summarize(total_pop = sum(pop))

ggplot(adult_pop_sum, aes(x = total_pop, y = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  xlab("Population") +
  ylab("Sex") +
  ggtitle("Populations of Wisconsin ZIP codes by Sex")

Generally speaking, zip codes with 0 or 100% of the male or female adults with a bachelors degree have a small population (the median population of adult males or females in a zip code is over 1100). Only one case has a higher population, where there are 100% of women with a bachelors degree and the population is listed as 2961.

This is an instance where the fact that the population is calculated from the obesity data (summarized on adults aged 18 and over) and the percentage of individuals with a bachelors degree (summarized on individuals aged 25 and older) is calculated on a different group can be very misleading.

Zip code 53706, is the UW Madison campus. Most, if not all of the women living in zip code 53706 will be residents in university housing and the vast majority will be under the age of 25. Hence, the 100% with a bachelors degree likely is based on a population much, much smaller than the recorded value of 2961; we just don’t know how small. The corresponding proportion of men with a bachelors degree in zip code 53706 is 44.4% which might be 4/9 or 8/18 or some other simple fraction with a small denominator.

In fact, the second largest population which appears on our list is zip code 54981, which is the UW-Oshkosh campus.

The next two zip codes on the list are small Wisconsin towns or villages (Packwaukee and Wilmot, WI) where it is plausible that a high percentage of the individuals are aged 25 and older and none have a bachelors degree.

Some other UW campuses with large residential college populations do not have their own zip code: for example, the UW Eau Claire campus shares its zip code with a substantial fraction of the surrounding city. Other campuses with their own zip code may not have had 0% or 100% or residents aged 25+ with our without a college degree, and so did not appear in this check of outliers. All of the remaining zip codes with 0% of adults aged 25+ from a single sex are likely actual from regions with very small populations and no one with a college degree.

Solution

prob6 = education %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(bs_degree = total_pop * pct_bachelors/100 ) %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarize(pct_bachelors = 100 *sum(bs_degree) / sum(total_pop))

  1. Create a summary of the obesity data named adult_obesity_sum which contains one row for each zip code and sex with counts of the number of obese individuals (obese_pop) and the total population (total_pop) of adults age 18+ by zip code and sex. Only include zip codes with no missing data for all eight adult age groups.

  • Specifically, filter out the rows with ages 5-17, filter out rows with any missing obesity data, add a variable which counts the number of remaining rows for each zip code, and filter out rows where this count is less than 8. Once you have completed filtering out zip codes that do not have complete obesity data for all adult age groups, then, you may sum the total number of obese individuals ans the total population for each remaining zip code.

  • If you have done this correctly, there are 306 zip codes with complete adult obesity data, so your obesity data set has \(306 \times 2 = 612\) rows.

  • Print the first ten rows of this data set.

Solution

adult_obesity_sum = obesity %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  filter(age != "05-17") %>% 
  group_by(zip) %>% 
  mutate(n_zip = n()) %>% 
  filter(n_zip == 8) %>% 
  group_by(zip, sex) %>% 
  summarize(obese_pop = sum(obese_pop),
            total_pop = sum(pop))

adult_obesity_sum %>% 
  print(n = 10)

  1. Join the adult_obesity_sum and the education data sets, joining by zip code and sex, keeping only zip code / sex combinations found in both data sets. (Use by = c("zip", "sex") to specify more than one joining variable.) Add a variable pct_obese which contains the percentage of obese individuals per zip code/sex.
  • Using this data set, create a scatter plot with the obesity percentage on the y-axis versus the education percentage on the x axis. Use different colors for each sex and add a smooth curve for each sex. Describe the pattern you see: how does obesity rate change among men and women as the population of zip codes increases?

Solution

prob8 = adult_obesity_sum %>% 
  select(-total_pop) %>% 
  inner_join(education, by = c("zip", "sex")) %>% 
  mutate(pct_obese = 100*obese_pop / total_pop)

ggplot(prob8, aes(x = pct_bachelors, y = pct_obese, color = sex)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(end = 0.5) +
  xlab("% adults 25+ with bachelors degree") +
  ylab("% obese") +
  ggtitle("Obesity versus college education in Wisconsin zip codes")

  • Zip codes with higher percentages of college educated people tend to have lower obesity rates.
  • It appears that obesity rates among men decrease a bit more slowly than among women as percentage of college educated adults increases
    • In zip codes with the lowest percentages of college education, obesity among women is a bit higher than among men.
    • In zip codes with the highest percentages of college education, obesity among women is a bit lower than among men.
  • But overall, the percentages are quite similar.
